030/**
031 * A palette of predefined colors as packed CIELAB floats, the kind {@link ColorTools} works with.
032 * You can access colors by their constant name, such as {@code OCEAN_BLUE}, by the {@link #NAMED} map using
033 * {@code NAMED.get("Ocean Blue", 0f)}, or by index in the FloatArray called {@link #LIST}. Note that to access a float
034 * color from NAMED, you need to give a default value if the name is not found; {@code 0f} is a good default because it
035 * will not occur in a valid CIELAB color. You can access the names in a specific order with {@link #NAMES} (which is
036 * alphabetical), {@link #NAMES_BY_HUE} (which is sorted by the hue of the matching color, from red to yellow to blue
037 * (with gray around here) to purple to red again), or {@link #NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS} (which is sorted by the intensity of
038 * the matching color, from darkest to lightest). Having a name lets you look up the matching color in {@link #NAMED}.
039 * <br>
040 * Created by Tommy Ettinger on 10/13/2020.
041 */
042public class Palette {
043    public static final ObjectFloatMap<String> NAMED = new ObjectFloatMap<String>(256);
044    public static final FloatArray LIST = new FloatArray(256);

3130    /**
3131     * All names for colors in this palette, sorted by lightness from black to white. You can fetch the
3132     * corresponding packed float color by looking up a name in {@link #NAMED}.
3133     */
3134    public static final Array<String> NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS = new Array<>(NAMES);
3135    static {
3136        NAMES_BY_HUE.sort(new Comparator<String>() {
3137            public int compare(String o1, String o2) {
3138                final float c1 = NAMED.get(o1, TRANSPARENT), c2 = NAMED.get(o2, TRANSPARENT);
3139                if(ColorTools.alphaInt(c1) < 128) return -10000;
3140                else if(ColorTools.alphaInt(c2) < 128) return 10000;
3141                final float s1 = ColorTools.saturation(c1), s2 = ColorTools.saturation(c2);
3142                if(s1 <= 0.05f && s2 > 0.05f)
3143                    return -1000;
3144                else if(s1 > 0.05f && s2 <= 0.05f)
3145                    return 1000;
3146                else if(s1 <= 0.05f && s2 <= 0.05f)
3147                    return (int)Math.signum(ColorTools.channelL(c1) - ColorTools.channelL(c2));
3148                else
3149                    return 2 * (int)Math.signum(ColorTools.hue(c1) - ColorTools.hue(c2))
3150                            + (int)Math.signum(ColorTools.channelL(c1) - ColorTools.channelL(c2));
3151            }
3152        });
3153        NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS.sort(new Comparator<String>() {
3154            public int compare(String o1, String o2) {
3155                return Float.compare(ColorTools.channelL(NAMED.get(o1, TRANSPARENT)), ColorTools.channelL(NAMED.get(o2, TRANSPARENT)));
3156            }
3157        });
3158    }

3160    /**
3161     * Changes the existing RGBA Color instances in {@link Colors} to use CIELAB and so be able to be shown normally by
3162     * {@link ColorfulBatch} or a Batch using {@link com.github.tommyettinger.colorful.Shaders#fragmentShaderCielab}.
3163     * Any colors used in libGDX text markup look up their values in Colors, so calling this can help display fonts
3164     * where markup is enabled. This only needs to be called once, and if you call {@link #appendToKnownColors()}, then
3165     * that should be done after this to avoid mixing RGBA and CIELAB colors.
3166     * <br>
3167     * This is a duplicate of a method with the same name in SimplePalette; you should still only call this method once,
3168     * regardless of where it was from.
3169     */
3170    public static void editKnownColors(){
3171        for(Color c : Colors.getColors().values()) {
3172            final float f = ColorTools.fromColor(c);
3173            c.set(channelL(f), channelA(f), channelB(f), c.a);
3174        }
3175    }

3177    /**
3178     * Appends CIELAB-compatible Color instances to the map in {@link Colors}, using the names in {@link #NAMES} (which
3179     * are "Title Cased" instead of "ALL UPPER CASE"). If you intend to still use the existing values in Colors, you
3180     * should call {@link #editKnownColors()} first; otherwise you can just always use "Title Cased" color names.
3181     * <br>
3182     * This can be used alongside the method with the same name in SimplePalette, since that uses "lower cased" names.
3183     */
3184    public static void appendToKnownColors(){
3185        for(ObjectFloatMap.Entry<String> ent : NAMED) {
3186            final float f = ent.value;
3187            Colors.put(ent.key, new Color(channelL(f), channelA(f), channelB(f), alpha(f)));
3188        }
3189    }
